# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1929-chicago-american-giants-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1920 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 51–19–2 record (45–15–2 in NNL games) and won the first NNL championship.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] Rube Foster was the team's owner and manager.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The team played its home games at Schorling Park in Chicago.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1921 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1921-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 55–28–4 record (44–22–2 against NNL opponents) and won the NNL pennant.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1922-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1922 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1922 baseball season.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1922-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 46–30–1 record (38–23–1 in NNL games) and won the NNL pennant for the third consecutive season.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1923-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1923 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1923 baseball season.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1923-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 48–29–1 record (42–29 in NNL games) and finished in second place in the NNL.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1923-chicago-american-giants-season] The independent Cleveland Tate Stars returned to the NNL as an associate member to finish the Tigers' schedule.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1923-chicago-american-giants-season] The team was not considered a full member of the NNL.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1924-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1924 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1924 baseball season.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1924-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 55–27 record (52–27 in NNL games) and finished in second place in the NNL.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1924-chicago-american-giants-season] †Indianapolis dropped out of the league in June and was replaced by Memphis.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1925-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1925 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1925 baseball season.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1925-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 57–43–2 record (52–42–2 in NNL games) and finished in fourth place in the NNL.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1926-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1926 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1926 baseball season.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1926-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 57–24–3 record (56–24–2 in NNL games), won the NNL pennant, and defeated the Bacharach Giants in the 1926 Colored World Series.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1926-chicago-american-giants-season] Rube Foster was the team's owner and first-half manager.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1926-chicago-american-giants-season] Dave Malarcher took over as manager in the second half of the season.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1926-chicago-american-giants-season] Other regular players included third baseman Dave Malarcher (.264 batting average), shortstop Sanford Jackson (.198 batting average), second baseman Charlie Williams (.246 batting average), center fielder George Sweatt (.271), catcher Pythias Russ (.275), and center fielder John Hines (.302).
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1926-chicago-american-giants-season] (1) First half champion (2) Second half champion †Cleveland folds mid-season before the conclusion of the season. §Dayton departs mid-season as an independent team, before the conclusion of the season.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1929-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1929 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1929 baseball season.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1929-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 62–42 record (50–38 in NNL games) and finished in third place in the NNL.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1929-chicago-american-giants-season] William Trimble was the team's owner, and Jim Brown was the team's manager.
[src:1929-chicago-american-giants-season/1929-chicago-american-giants-season] The team played its home games at South Side Park in Chicago.
